    "# Objective"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are a lot of features in this dataset (18 behavioral features). We will now perform:<br>\n",
    "* Data preprocessing<br>\n",
    "* Clustering<br>\n",
    "* Feature extraction to improve clustering<br>\n",
    "* Experiment with various clustering models: KMeans, Agglomerative Hierarchical, Gaussian Mixture<br>\n",
    "* Choosing the number of clusters<br>\n",
    "* EDA to segment the customers<br>\n",
    "* Concluding the project by giving marketing strategy based on what we learn from the data"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Data Description"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Link to the dataset: [Kaggle link](https://www.kaggle.com/arjunbhasin2013/ccdata/downloads/ccdata.zip/1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Following is the Data Dictionary for Credit Card dataset:<br>\n",
    "* CUST_ID: Identification of Credit Card holder (Categorical)<br>\n",
    "* BALANCE: Balance amount left in their account to make purchases<br>\n",
    "* BALANCE_FREQUENCY: How frequently the Balance is updated, score between 0 and 1 (1 = frequently updated, 0 = not frequently updated)<br>\n",
    "* PURCHASES: Amount of purchases made from account<br>\n",
    "* ONEOFF_PURCHASES: Maximum purchase amount done in one-go<br>\n",
    "* INSTALLMENTS_PURCHASES: Amount of purchase done in installment<br>\n",
    "* CASH_ADVANCE: Cash in advance given by the user<br>\n",
    "* PURCHASES_FREQUENCY: How frequently the Purchases are being made, score between 0 and 1 (1 = frequently purchased, 0 = not frequently purchased)<br>\n",
    "* ONEOFFPURCHASESFREQUENCY: How frequently Purchases are happening in one-go (1 = frequently purchased, 0 = not frequently purchased)<br>\n",
    "* PURCHASESINSTALLMENTSFREQUENCY: How frequently purchases in installments are being done (1 = frequently done, 0 = not frequently done)<br>\n",
    "* CASHADVANCEFREQUENCY: How frequently the cash in advance being paid<br>\n",
    "* CASHADVANCETRX: Number of Transactions made with \"Cash in Advanced\"<br>\n",
    "* PURCHASES_TRX: Number of purchase transactions made<br>\n",
    "* CREDIT_LIMIT: Limit of Credit Card for user<br>\n",
    "* PAYMENTS: Amount of Payment done by user<br>\n",
    "* MINIMUM_PAYMENTS: Minimum amount of payments made by user<br>\n",
    "* PRCFULLPAYMENT: Percent of full payment paid by user<br>\n",
    "* TENURE: Tenure of credit card service for user"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2019-06-30T12:46:34.208829Z",

    "# import necessary tools\n",

    "\n",
    "# preprocessing\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "\n",
    "# ignore warnings\n",
    "import warnings\n",
    "warnings.filterwarnings(action=\"ignore\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# clustering\n",
    "from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, AgglomerativeClustering\n",
    "from sklearn.mixture import GaussianMixture\n",
    "from matplotlib import cm\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples, silhouette_score"
   ]

    "## Clustering using K-Means"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this section we will perform K-Means clustering on the data and check the clustering metrics (inertia, silhouette scores)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Inertia Plot"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "First, we make the inertia plot:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2019-06-30T12:46:48.719309Z",
     "start_time": "2019-06-30T12:46:48.707764Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# inertia plotter function\n",
    "def inertia_plot(clust, X, start = 2, stop = 20):\n",
    "    inertia = []\n",
    "    for x in range(start,stop):\n",
    "        km = clust(n_clusters = x)\n",
    "        labels = km.fit_predict(X)\n",
    "        inertia.append(km.inertia_)\n",
    "    plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))\n",
    "    plt.plot(range(start,stop), inertia, marker = 'o')\n",
    "    plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')\n",
    "    plt.ylabel('Inertia')\n",
    "    plt.title('Inertia plot with K')\n",
    "    plt.xticks(list(range(start, stop)))\n",
    "    plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2019-06-30T12:47:11.369713Z",
     "start_time": "2019-06-30T12:46:52.992345Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x432 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "inertia_plot(KMeans, data_imputed)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Using the elbow method, we pick a good number of clusters to be 6."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Silhouette Scores"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Silhouette analysis can be used to study the separation distance between the resulting clusters. The silhouette plot displays a measure of how close each point in one cluster is to points in the neighboring clusters and thus provides a way to assess parameters like number of clusters visually. This measure has a range of [-1, 1]."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We will now check the silhouette scores for different numbers of clusters. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2019-06-30T12:47:11.390869Z",
     "start_time": "2019-06-30T12:47:11.375460Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def silh_samp_cluster(clust,  X, start=2, stop=5, metric = 'euclidean'):\n",
    "    # taken from sebastian Raschkas book Python Machine Learning second edition\n",
    "    for x in range(start, stop):\n",
    "        km = clust(n_clusters = x)\n",
    "        y_km = km.fit_predict(X)\n",
    "        cluster_labels = np.unique(y_km)\n",
    "        n_clusters = cluster_labels.shape[0]\n",
    "        silhouette_vals = silhouette_samples(X, y_km, metric = metric)\n",
    "        y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper =0,0\n",
    "        yticks = []\n",
    "        for i, c in enumerate(cluster_labels):\n",
    "            c_silhouette_vals = silhouette_vals[y_km == c]\n",
    "            c_silhouette_vals.sort()\n",
    "            y_ax_upper += len(c_silhouette_vals)\n",
    "            color = cm.jet(float(i)/n_clusters)\n",
    "            plt.barh(range(y_ax_lower, y_ax_upper),\n",
    "                    c_silhouette_vals,\n",
    "                    height=1.0,\n",
    "                    edgecolor='none',\n",
    "                    color = color)\n",
    "            yticks.append((y_ax_lower + y_ax_upper)/2.)\n",
    "            y_ax_lower+= len(c_silhouette_vals)\n",
    "\n",
    "        silhouette_avg = np.mean(silhouette_vals)\n",
    "        plt.axvline(silhouette_avg,\n",
    "                   color = 'red',\n",
    "                   linestyle = \"--\")\n",
    "        plt.yticks(yticks, cluster_labels+1)\n",
    "        plt.ylabel(\"cluster\")\n",
    "        plt.xlabel('Silhouette Coefficient')\n",
    "        plt.title('Silhouette for ' + str(x) + \" Clusters\")\n",
    "        plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2019-06-30T12:47:24.052057Z",
     "start_time": "2019-06-30T12:47:11.396866Z"
    },
    "scrolled": false
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Silhouette-Score for 2 Clusters:  0.20960465116695418\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 3 Clusters:  0.2508020421643232\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 4 Clusters:  0.1976791965228765\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 5 Clusters:  0.19029814154984043\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 6 Clusters:  0.20263819385025553\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "for x in range(2, 7):\n",
    "    alg = KMeans(n_clusters = x, )\n",
    "    label = alg.fit_predict(data_imputed)\n",
    "    print('Silhouette-Score for', x,  'Clusters: ', silhouette_score(data_imputed, label))"
   ]
  },

    "So far, we have a high average inertia, low silhouette scores, and very wide fluctuations in the size of the silhouette plots. This is not good. Let's apply feature extraction with PCA to improve clustering."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Feature Extraction with PCA"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Clustering Metrics"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we will apply PCA to improve clustering. We should be able to see lower inertias and higher silhouette scores after feature extraction."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {
    "ExecuteTime": {
     "end_time": "2019-06-30T12:51:00.601142Z",
     "start_time": "2019-06-30T12:50:15.710107Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "PCA with # of components:  2\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 2 Clusters:  0.46465479431270534        Inertia:  49682.73274051301\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 3 Clusters:  0.4518351583555225        Inertia:  33031.47401545379\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 4 Clusters:  0.4073585864501941        Inertia:  24544.24482589567\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 5 Clusters:  0.4006605339188969        Inertia:  19475.027618054555\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 6 Clusters:  0.3831171886914103        Inertia:  16227.77126102003\n",
      "\n",
      "PCA with # of components:  3\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 2 Clusters:  0.34138059980809216        Inertia:  62045.14795760842\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 3 Clusters:  0.3797307331170353        Inertia:  46325.34921425197\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 4 Clusters:  0.369279814360067        Inertia:  34659.74111687311\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 5 Clusters:  0.36831384998922845        Inertia:  28591.733482974614\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 6 Clusters:  0.3314415719819512        Inertia:  24847.61783847582\n",
      "\n",
      "PCA with # of components:  4\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 2 Clusters:  0.3057392880087437        Inertia:  73184.92491408344\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 3 Clusters:  0.3432745593601783        Inertia:  57561.006831771716\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 4 Clusters:  0.3219180239069211        Inertia:  45288.0674784414\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 5 Clusters:  0.31998686049621133        Inertia:  39166.378524827924\n",
      "Silhouette-Score for 6 Clusters:  0.2884156635668477        Inertia:  35301.53554112003\n",
      "\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# apply PCA and display clustering metrics\n",
    "for y in range(2, 5):\n",
    "    print(\"PCA with # of components: \", y)\n",
    "    pca = PCA(n_components=y)\n",
    "    data_p = pca.fit_transform(data_imputed)\n",
    "    for x in range(2, 7):\n",
    "        alg = KMeans(n_clusters = x, )\n",
    "        label = alg.fit_predict(data_p)\n",
    "        print('Silhouette-Score for', x,  'Clusters: ', silhouette_score(data_p, label) , '       Inertia: ',alg.inertia_)\n",
    "    print()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As you can see, 2 PCA components with 5-6 clusters would be our best bet. "
   ]

    "sns.pairplot(data_final[best_cols], hue='cluster', x_vars=['PURCHASES'], y_vars=['PAYMENTS'],\n",
    "            height=5, aspect=1)"
   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Summary and Possible Marketing Strategy"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We have learned a lot from this dataset by segmenting the customers into six smaller groups: the Average Joe, the Active Users, the Big Spenders, the Money Borrowers, the High Riskers, and the Wildcards. To conclude this cluster analysis, let's sum up what we have learned and some possible marketing strategies:<br>\n",
    "* The Average Joe do not use credit card very much in their daily life. They have healthy finances and low debts. While encouraging these people to use credit cards more is necessary for the company's profit, business ethics and social responsibility should also be considered.<br>\n",
    "<br>\n",
    "* Identify active customers in order to apply proper marketing strategy towards them. These people are the main group that we should focus on.<br>\n",
    "<br>\n",
    "* Some people are just bad at finance management - for example, the Money Borrowers. This should not be taken lightly.<br>\n",
    "<br>\n",
    "* Although we are currently doing a good job at managing the High Riskers by giving them low credit limits, more marketing strategies targeting this group of customers should be considered.<br>"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Conclusion"

"
